Question: Java SAX parsing. Getting access to file lines in the currently parsing xml file: :When parsing an XML document, you can set a locator, the locator will tell you what current line and column number your are currently on when different events fire. I am wondering, how can I get the contents of the line, do I have to pass the file, read it into an array myself, isn't this already done by the sax handler, since it is giving me access to the locator, there has to be away to also access the file that the handler is currently working with. Thanks! ::::::::::::::::::::::::::EDIT:::::::::::::::::::I am trying to echo an xml file and want doctype declarations to be included: <!DOCTYPE employee [<!ELEMENT employee (Name, Dept, Title)><!ELEMENT Name (#PCDATA)> <!ELEMENT Dept (#PCDATA)><!ELEMENT Title (#PCDATA)> ]>There is a public void startDTD(String name, String publicId, String systemId);and a public void endDTD();Where you can use the locator to get current line and column, and read from file.There are a couple of things that the SAX parser does not fire events on or give sufficient information as to what was in the read XML file. 
Please using this api: InputStream.read.
Answer: <<<api>>>: InputStream.read
<<<code>>>: 
```
int c;
while ((c = in.read()) != -1) {
    // do something with c
}
```
<<<explanation>>>: This will read the file byte by byte. You can use the read() method of the InputStream class to read the file byte by byte. The read() method returns an int value which is the byte read, or -1 if the end of the stream has been reached. You can use this value to do whatever you want with the byte, such as printing it out.

Please note that this will only give you the raw bytes of the file, not the characters that those bytes represent. If you want to read the file as a sequence of characters, you will need to use a Reader, such as InputStreamReader, which can convert the bytes to characters.

Also, be aware that this will only work if the file is small enough to fit into memory. If the file is too large to fit into memory, you will need to use a different approach, such as reading the file in chunks.

This approach does not give you access to the line number or column number of the characters in the file. If you need this information, you will need to keep track of it yourself, which can be a bit tricky because the file can contain newline characters (which indicate the end of a line) but can also contain carriage return and linefeed characters (which are part of a line).

If you need to read the file line by line, you can use a BufferedReader, which can read the file line by line, or use the readLine() method of the BufferedReader class. This will give you the next line of the file as a String, or null if the end of the file has been reached.

Here is an example of how to use a BufferedReader to read the file line by line:

```java
BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader("filename"));
String line;
while ((line = reader.readLine()) != null) {
    System.out.println(line);
}
```

This will print out each line of the file, one line at a time.

Please note that the BufferedReader class is part of the java.io package, not the java.util package. You will need to import the BufferedReader class and the FileReader class at the top of your file:

```java
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.FileReader;
```

